Visualising spatial data in R

David Jogensen

Spatial data in R

R can act as a fast, free, user friendly graphical information system (GIS) but some work is required to get used to dealing with spatial data in R. The two main types of spatial data you will encounter are raster data (usually high resolution images) and vector data (points, lines and polygons). This tutorial will focus on vector data as this is the more common format for data input, with rasters usually produced as an output from previous analysis.

The rgdal package is important for reading and transforming vector data in R, it acts as an interface with the C spatial data processing library gdal from within R. WHO geodatabases have been downloaded from http://hub.arcgis.com/ where they are publicly available. Copy these to your computer and set your working directory to the file you have copied them to. The admin 1 and 2 datasets have been converted to .RData format using R, this is an efficient data storage system in R which allows you to save and load objects in your environment to use in the future or share with others. We will import the disputed areas from an ESRI Shapefile to show you how to use the readOGR function

require(rgdal)
# input shapefiles
DISPUTED_AREAS <- readOGR(dsn = "./DISPUTED_AREAS/DISPUTED_AREAS.shp")
load("./GLOBAL_ADM1.Rdata")
load("./ADM_2_PK.RData")

The readOGR command above uses only the dsn arguement which stands for data source name. When importing full geodatabases with multiple layers (for example the WHO also provides map files in a .gdb format with all admin levels together) the layer arguement can be used to select which layer to extract in to the R data environment.

Plot GLOBAL_ADM1 with the plot command in R. As you can see, the map covers the whole world, we want to extract only Pakistan from the GLOBAL_ADM1 file, and only Jammu and Kashmir from the DISPUTED_AREAS. As districts and provinces have been renamed over time we also need to make sure we only extract the current borders for each region. We do this by making sure the end date given in the file is later than today’s date using Sys.Date in R. Try running Sys.Date() in your console and it should return today’s date. The following commands extract Afghanistan from the GLOBAL_ADM1 data and Kashmir from the DISPUTED_AREAS. Write your own code to extract Pakistan from the GLOBAL_ADM1 data (hint: ISO2 code for Pakistan is PK):

ADM_1_AF <- GLOBAL_ADM1[GLOBAL_ADM1@data$ISO_2_CODE=="AF" & as.Date(GLOBAL_ADM1@data$ENDDATE)>=Sys.Date(),]

JK <- DISPUTED_AREAS[DISPUTED_AREAS@data$NAME=="Jammu and Kashmir",]

ADM_1_PK <- 
ADM_1_PK <- GLOBAL_ADM1[GLOBAL_ADM1@data$ISO_2_CODE=="PK" 
                        & as.Date(GLOBAL_ADM1@data$ENDDATE)>=Sys.Date(),]

JK <- DISPUTED_AREAS[DISPUTED_AREAS@data$NAME=="Jammu and Kashmir",]

Remove the ADM_1_AF dataset from your environment. For the Admin 2 level data Pakistan has already been extracted for you.

You may notice some notation in the code above which you have not seen before. As spatial data includes point or polygon data alongside a data table, these are stored separately within the data object. Run View(ADM_2_PK) in your console, you should see a number of different slots within the object which can be accessed using the @ symbol The key slots for plotting and ammending the data are the @data slot which contains an attribute data table for each region in the shapefile and the @polygons slot which contains the data needed to plot the boundaries. To access columns within the @data table we can then use the dollar operator as you have seen previously. For example ADM_1_PK@data$ADM1_NAME should return the names of all the provinces in Pakistan:

ADM_1_PK@data$ADM1_NAME
## [1] AJK              BALOCHISTAN      GILGIT BALTISTAN ISLAMABAD       
## [5] PUNJAB           SINDH            FATA             KHYBER PAKHTOON 
## 3139 Levels: Å UMADIJSKI UPRAVNI OKRUG A&N ISLANDS Ä°MIÅžLI ... ZURRIEQ

Plotting only a portion of the map is as simple as subsetting any other data frame. The code below plots districts in Sindh only:

plot(ADM_2_PK[ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME=="SINDH",])

Try plotting only the Islamabad Capital territory, check in the ADM_2_PK@data with the View function to see what the capital territory is named in the map file, it is included within Islamabad province. Your output should look like the one below:

plot(ADM_2_PK[ADM_2_PK$ADM2_NAME=="ICT",])

If we want to colour certain districts to highlight them this can be carried out in plot using the same subsetting process. Using the plot function, if we want to add a layer to an existing map we need to write an additional plot command with add=TRUE:

plot(ADM_2_PK, col="seashell")
plot(ADM_2_PK[ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME=="SINDH",], col="forestgreen", add=TRUE)

This plot uses pre-programmed colours in R, full lists with the colurs shown can be found online by searching “colour in R”. To see the names of all the colours programmed in R run colors() in your console.

Try plotting Jammu and Kashmir on this map with the colour lightgrey, you will see that this covers up the districts in G-B and AJK. using the plot function it is not possible to add this layer behind the existing layers, if you try plotting JK first you will see that this limits the extent of the plot and most of the country is cut off. To go further with mapping we will use ggplot2!

# Adding JK to the existing plot
plot(ADM_2_PK, col="seashell")
plot(ADM_2_PK[ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME=="SINDH",], col="forestgreen", add=TRUE)
plot(JK, col="lightgrey", add=TRUE)

# trying to plot JK first
plot(JK, col="lightgrey")
plot(ADM_2_PK, col="seashell", add=TRUE)
plot(ADM_2_PK[ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME=="SINDH",], col="forestgreen", add=TRUE)

ggplot for mapping

ggplot is a good alternative to base graphics in R. It allows much more to be done with maps in R but as it was not specifically designed to reproduce maps some work needs to be done to get map data in to a format which can be recognised by ggplot. First we will load up ggplot and try plottign the admin 2 data from before:

require(ggplot2)
ggplot(ADM_2_PK)

You will get a blank plot. To plot polygon data with ggplot we first need to fortify the data uing the maptools package.

require(maptools)
ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY <- fortify(ADM_2_PK)

This converts the spatial data object in to a data.frame which can be plotted with ggplot. ggplot is not able to deal with spatial objects directly as you can do with the plot function. Run View(ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY) in your console. You will see that all of the attributes in the data frame have also been removed.

To plot this fortified map with ggplot we will need to specify that we wish to plot polygon data (geom_polygon) and specify which columns in the data represent the x (longitude) and y (latitude) data. We also need to specify the column which contains the group of the polygon data. This is what tells ggplot which polygon each data point belongs to.

ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data=ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group), size=1)

This will plot a stretched map which doesn’t appear to show the polygons, we need to specifiy a line colour to see the polygons and use coord_map so that R knows we want to use a map co-ordinate system.

ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data=ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group),color="black", size=1)+
  coord_map()

In ggplot we can add different layers to the plot using + rather than stacking multiple plots. As all of the layers are built together we can change their order to change which layer is plotted first without changing the extent. In the below example we fortify the JK polygon and plot this behind the polygons for the whole of Pakistan and use the fill arguement to change the colour of the polygons. we will save this plot to the R environment using <-

JK_FORTIFY <- fortify(JK)

Pak_map <- ggplot()+
  geom_polygon(data=JK_FORTIFY, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group), color="black", fill="grey")+
  geom_polygon(data=ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group),color="black", fill="seashell")+
  coord_map()

To remove the background from ggplots we can add the following to the ggplot command we have just run. As we have saved the previous plot as a ggplot object we can add further commands using + . Background elements are all editied from within the theme command (theme()):

 Pak_map + theme(axis.line=element_blank(),           # remove axis lines
                 axis.text.x=element_blank(),         # remove x axis numbers
                 axis.text.y=element_blank(),         # remove y axis numbers
                 axis.ticks=element_blank(),          # remove markers for the numbers
                 axis.title.x=element_blank(),        # remove x axis title 
                 axis.title.y=element_blank(),        # remove y axis title
                 panel.background=element_blank(),    # remove the white background around the axes
                 panel.border=element_blank(),        # remove the border around the plot
                 panel.grid.major=element_blank(),    # remove grid lines
                 panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),    # remove grid lines
                 plot.background=element_blank(),     # remove the grey background
                 plot.margin=unit(c(0,0,0,0), "cm"))  # remove empty space around the plot

We can also add annotations to the ggplot object using annotate and the coordinates of the point we want to label, update Pak_map in your environment by overwriting it with this new map:

 Pak_map <- Pak_map + theme(axis.line=element_blank(),     
                 axis.text.x=element_blank(),     
                 axis.text.y=element_blank(),   
                 axis.ticks=element_blank(),  
                 axis.title.x=element_blank(),   
                 axis.title.y=element_blank(),        
                 panel.background=element_blank(),   
                 panel.border=element_blank(),        
                 panel.grid.major=element_blank(),    
                 panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),    
                 plot.background=element_blank(),     
                 plot.margin=unit(c(0,0,0,0), "cm"))+
  annotate("text", x = 76.5, y = 33.8, label = "Disputed Territory", size= 3.5)

# running the name of a ggplot object will plot the object for you
Pak_map

All of our plots so far have been blank with no associated data to plot. we will now import some of the polio data provided for the course and try plotting this with ggplot.

Plotting some data

Adding data to the existing spatial polygons data frames allows us to plot different attributes on the maps. In these examples we will use three types of polio data you are likely to come accross regularly.

LQAS

Read in the LQAS percentage pass file and save as LQAS_PASS in your environment. The columns we need to match this data to the maps are named differently so we need to rename these to match. Add your own code to rename “District” as “ADM2_NAME”

LQAS_PASS <- read_excel("../LQAS %Pass _ District level_ Sep18-Mar19.xlsx")
colnames(LQAS_PASS)[colnames(LQAS_PASS)=="Province"] <- "ADM1_NAME"
colnames(LQAS_PASS)[colnames(LQAS_PASS)=="District"] <- "ADM2_NAME"

Some province and district names are also not matched to the map data we have been working with. To see which these are use the %in% command.

ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME[!ADM_2_PK$ADM1_NAME %in% LQAS_PASS$ADM1_NAME]
ADM_2_PK$ADM2_NAME[!ADM_2_PK$ADM2_NAME %in% LQAS_PASS$ADM2_NAME]

Using View to look at the LQAS_PASS data we can see that a number of the province names are shortened in the data frame. Use the following code to replace the district and province names with the ones used in the map data using dplyr:

# Province names shortened in LQAS data frame - change to long form (match map)
require(dplyr)

LQAS_PASS$ADM1_NAME <- recode(LQAS_PASS$ADM1_NAME, 
                            "KP"="KHYBER PAKHTOON",
                              "BALOCH"="BALOCHISTAN",
                              "GB"="GILGIT BALTISTAN",
                              "KPTD"="FATA",
                              "ISB"="ISLAMABAD"
                            )
# Different district spellings
LQAS_PASS$ADM2_NAME <- recode(LQAS_PASS$ADM2_NAME, 
                               "UMERKOT"="UMARKOT",
                                 "DIAMER"="DIAMIR",
                                 "SHEIKHUPURA"="SHEIKUPURA",
                                 "BUNER"="BUNIR"
                            )

If we make a copy of the @data slot from ADM_2_PK we can match the data we wish to add to the rows already present in the table. Adding an id column allows us to match these rows to the fortified data:

ADM_2_PK@data$id <- rownames(ADM_2_PK@data)
# merge the data matching by administrative level names
temp_mapdata <- merge(ADM_2_PK@data, LQAS_PASS, by=c("ADM1_NAME","ADM2_NAME"), all=T)
FORTIFY_LQAS<- merge(ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY, temp_mapdata[,c("id", "%Pass")], by="id")

Now we can plot this data using ggplot. For this example we will add it to the existing Pak_map we created earlier as a new polygon layer. we will add a parameter to the aesthetics specifying that we wish to fill by %pass. as this column starts with a special character we need to put it in back quotes otherwise we will get an error in R. You could also rename the column to fix this issue.

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=FORTIFY_LQAS, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group, fill=`%Pass`))

This will give a heat map of percentage pass per district but when looking at LQAS we are interested in the cutoff points for high pass, pass, fail etc. To specify these cut points in the aesthetics of the plot we can use cut(). This function also lets us specify labels for each of the sections we cut the data in to:

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=FORTIFY_LQAS,
                  aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group, 
                        fill=cut(`%Pass`, c(-Inf,79.5,84.5,89.5,94.5,Inf),
                              labels=c("<80%","80-84%","85-89%","90-94%","95%+"))),
                  color="grey")

This map will be ugly but will incorporate the cut points we have specified and their labels. We now need to edit the legend for this fill to fix the title and choose colours for each of the cut points we have chosen. For the colours I have used HEX colours, google HEX colour picker to see how these work. These can be directly entered in to R in place of the pre-programmed colours we used earlier.

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=FORTIFY_LQAS, 
                       aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group,
                           fill=cut(`%Pass`, c(-Inf,79.5,84.5,89.5,94.5,Inf),
                                    labels=c("<80%","80-84%","85-89%","90-94%","95%+"))),
                       color="grey")+
    scale_fill_manual(
      name="% Lot Pass", # Name for the legend
      values = c("#e30000", "#e8ab02", "#c9f2b6", "#46a649", "#29782b", "white"),
      na.value="white") # specify some colours

We can plot the Provinces over this map using geom_path. This will plot only the outlines of the polygons so that we can see the data plotted below:

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=FORTIFY_LQAS,
                aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group,
                    fill=cut(`%Pass`, c(-Inf,79.5,84.5,89.5,94.5,Inf),
                            labels=c("<80%","80-84%","85-89%","90-94%","95%+"))),
                color="grey")+
    scale_fill_manual(name="% Lot Pass", # Name for the legend
                values = c("#e30000", "#e8ab02", "#c9f2b6", "#46a649", "#29782b", "white"),
                na.value="white")+ 
    geom_path(data=ADM_1_PK, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group), colour="black", size=1)

Non-polio AFP rate

To plot the NPAFP rate we first have to calculate it from the population and the number of reported cases on NPAFP. Datasets for both of these have been provided. Read in the population data from the excel file and name it POP.

POP <- read_excel("../Population under 15-estimates 2018-19 as 190510.xlsx")

There is a total at the bottom of the population column which we will need to remove, this can be done with the following code or removed in excel before importing the data.

POP <- POP[-c(171),]

Also import the non-polio AFP rate data and name this NPAFP.

NPAFP <- read_excel("../List of NON POLIO AFP Cases 2015-2019.xlsx", range = cell_cols("A:N"))

We will extract 2018 and 2019 from the NPAFP dataset as these are the years we want to plot.

NPAFP18_19 <- NPAFP[NPAFP$YRONSET %in% c("2018","2019"),]

Both of these files have column names “PROVINCE” and “DISTRICT”, rename these in the same way we did for the LQAS data.

colnames(NPAFP18_19)[colnames(NPAFP18_19)=="PROVINCE"] <- "ADM1_NAME"
colnames(NPAFP18_19)[colnames(NPAFP18_19)=="DISTRICT"] <- "ADM2_NAME"
colnames(POP)[colnames(POP)=="PROVINCE"] <- "ADM1_NAME"
colnames(POP)[colnames(POP)=="DISTRICT"] <- "ADM2_NAME"

We want to sum the non-polio AFP cases by district and year of onset, we can do that with the following code by adding a column of 1s that we can sum to give a count. We then use reshape2 to cast the table in to a more traditional data frame with columns for each year and rows for each district.

NPAFP18_19$CASE <- 1 # add a column to sum
NPAFP18_19_ag <- aggregate(CASE ~ YRONSET + ADM2_NAME, NPAFP18_19, sum) #sum
require(reshape2)
NPAFP18_19_ag <- dcast(NPAFP18_19_ag, ADM2_NAME~YRONSET) # transform into wide format

One district does not match between these datasets so needs to be changed before merging. we will then merge the count data with the population data and crete new rate columns per 10000 people under 15:

NPAFP18_19_ag$ADM2_NAME <- recode(NPAFP18_19_ag$ADM2_NAME, "JEHLUM_VALLEY"="HATTIAN")

NPAFP_R8 <- merge(NPAFP18_19_ag, POP, by="ADM2_NAME", all=T)
NPAFP_R8$RATE_18 <- (NPAFP_R8$`2018`/NPAFP_R8$`POPL15 (2018)`)*100000
NPAFP_R8$RATE_19 <- (NPAFP_R8$`2019`/NPAFP_R8$`POPL15 (2019)`)*100000

We then need to rename the districts and provinces to match the map data and plot as we did for the previous example.

NPAFP_R8$ADM1_NAME <- recode(NPAFP_R8$ADM1_NAME, 
                                "KP"="KHYBER PAKHTOON",
                                "GBALTISTAN"="GILGIT BALTISTAN",
                                "KPTD"="FATA"
                               )
NPAFP_R8$ADM2_NAME <- recode(NPAFP_R8$ADM2_NAME, 
                              "UMERKOT"="UMARKOT",
                              "DIAMER"="DIAMIR",
                              "SHEIKHUPURA"="SHEIKUPURA",
                              "BUNER"="BUNIR"
                              )


temp_mapdata <- merge(ADM_2_PK@data, NPAFP_R8, by=c("ADM2_NAME"), all=T)

NPAFP_FORTIFY <- merge(ADM_2_PK_FORTIFY, temp_mapdata[,c("id", "RATE_18", "RATE_19")], by="id")

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=NPAFP_FORTIFY,
                aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group,
                    fill=cut(RATE_19, c(-Inf,0.99,1.99,3.99,5.99,Inf),
                            labels=c("0.00-0.99","1.00-1.99","2.00-3.99","4.00-5.99","6.00+"))),
                color="grey")+
          geom_path(data=ADM_1_PK, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group),
                    colour="black", size=1)+
          scale_fill_manual(name="NPAFP rate per 100000",
                      values = c("#e30000", "#e8ab02", "#c9f2b6", "#46a649", "#29782b", "white"),
                      na.value="white", drop=F)

This plots a map for 2019 to date, look at the code and see if you can plot the same map for 2018.

Pak_map + geom_polygon(data=NPAFP_FORTIFY,
                aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group, 
                    fill=cut(RATE_18, c(-Inf,0.99,1.99,3.99,5.99,Inf),
                             labels=c("0.00-0.99","1.00-1.99","2.00-3.99","4.00-5.99","6.00+"))),
                color="grey")+
          geom_path(data=ADM_1_PK, aes(y=lat, x=long, group=group),
                    colour="black", size=1)+
          scale_fill_manual(name="NPAFP rate per 100000",
                      values = c("#e30000", "#e8ab02", "#c9f2b6", "#46a649", "#29782b", "white"),
                      na.value="white", drop=F)

Case data

To plot case data we need to use points rather than filling the polygons. A dataset of all AFP cases is provided, import this in to R and extract only WPV1 cases from the VIRUS column in to a data frame called PV_cases. The “PROVINCE” and “DISTRICT” columns will also need to be renamed as before. NOTE: we want sheet 3 from this excel spreadsheet, this can be specified with sheet=3

ALL_AFP <- read_excel("../List of AFP Cases 2015-2019.xlsx", sheet=3)
PV_Cases <- ALL_AFP[ALL_AFP$VIRUS=="WPV1",]
colnames(PV_Cases)[colnames(PV_Cases)=="PROVINCE"] <- "ADM1_NAME"
colnames(PV_Cases)[colnames(PV_Cases)=="DISTRICT"] <- "ADM2_NAME"

Some names don’t match the map data:

PV_Cases$ADM1_NAME <- recode(PV_Cases$ADM1_NAME, 
                               "KP"="KHYBER PAKHTOON",
                                 "GBALTISTAN"="GILGIT BALTISTAN",
                                 "KPTD"="FATA"
                               )
# Different district spellings
PV_Cases$ADM2_NAME <- recode(PV_Cases$ADM2_NAME, 
                               "UMERKOT"="UMARKOT",
                                 "DIAMER"="DIAMIR",
                                 "SHEIKHUPURA"="SHEIKUPURA",
                                 "BUNER"="BUNIR"
                               )

We will sum polio cases in the same way as the non-polio AFP cases. Adapt the code given above for NPAFP and apply to PV_Cases. Name the output file PV_Cases_sum.

PV_Cases$CASE <- 1 # add a column to sum
PV_Cases_sum <- aggregate(CASE ~ YRONSET + ADM2_NAME, PV_Cases, sum) #sum
PV_Cases_sum <- dcast(PV_Cases_sum, ADM2_NAME~YRONSET) # transform into wide format

This time we will create a copy of the spatial polygons data frame and attach our new data to this. We do not need to fortify to plot point data on a map:

ADM_2_PK_Cases <- ADM_2_PK
ADM_2_PK_Cases <- raster::aggregate(ADM_2_PK_Cases, by=c("ADM1_NAME", "ADM2_NAME"), all=T)
ADM_2_PK_Cases@data$id <- rownames(ADM_2_PK_Cases@data)

temp_mapdata <- merge(ADM_2_PK_Cases@data, PV_Cases_sum, by=c("ADM2_NAME"), all=T)

# set all the NA values to 0
temp_mapdata[is.na(temp_mapdata$`2019`),]$`2019` <- 0
temp_mapdata[is.na(temp_mapdata$`2018`),]$`2018` <- 0
temp_mapdata[is.na(temp_mapdata$`2017`),]$`2017` <- 0
temp_mapdata[is.na(temp_mapdata$`2016`),]$`2016` <- 0
temp_mapdata[is.na(temp_mapdata$`2015`),]$`2015` <- 0

ADM_2_PK_Cases@data <- merge(ADM_2_PK_Cases@data,temp_mapdata, by=c("id"), all=T)

We need to set all of the NA values in the table to 0 in order to work with the function we use to plot the data. As we do not have exact locations for the cases we can approximate their locations using the dotsInPolys function. This will plot the correct number of cases randomly within the district where they were reported, which is not accurate but can be used as a visual aid in a presentation or document. Not providing exact locations helps to annonymise the identity of polio patients.

try2019 <- data.frame(dotsInPolys(ADM_2_PK_Cases, as.integer(ADM_2_PK_Cases$`2019`)))

Pak_map + geom_point(data=try2019, aes(y=y, x=x),shape=21, size=3, fill="red")

Try adapting the code to plot cases for different years.
